@node t-psupen.psu.edu
PENPages

telnet @{"psupen.psu.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open psupen.psu.edu\r'"}

User name: Your 2-letter state code or WORLD

Run by Pennsylvania State University's College of Agricultural Sciences.
PENPages, provides weekly world weather and crop reports from the U.S.
Department of Agriculture. These reports detail everything from the
effect of the weather on palm  trees in Malaysia to the state of the
Ukrainian wheat crop. Reports from Pennsylvania country extension
officers offer tips for improving farm life. One database lists
Pennsylvania hay distributors by county - and rates the quality of their
hay! The service lets you search for information two different ways. A
menu system  gives you quick access to reports that change frequently,
such as the weekly  crop/weather reports. An index system lets you
search through several thousand  online documents by keyword. At the
main menu, you can either browse through an online manual or choose
"PENPages," which puts you into the agriculture system.

@endnode

@node t-callcat.med.miami.edu
The University of Miami

telnet @{"callcat.med.miami.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open callcat.med.miami.edu\r'"}

Log in: @{"library" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'library\r'"}

The University of Miami maintains a database of AIDS health
providers in southern  Florida. At the main menu, select `P' (for
"AIDS providers") and you'll be able to search for  doctors, hospitals
and other providers that care for patients with AIDS.  You can also
search by speciality.

@endnode

@node t-ham.njit.edu 2000
The National Ham Radio Call-Sign Callbook

telnet @{"callsign.cs.buffalo.edu 2000" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open callsign.cs.buffalo.edu 2000\r'"} or @{"ham.njit.edu 2000" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ham.njit.edu 2000\r'"}

The National Ham Radio Call-Sign Callbook lets you search for
American amateur  operators by callsign, city, last name or Zip code.
A successful search will give you  the ham's name, address, callsign,
age, type of license and when he or she got it. When you
connect, you  tell the system how you want to search and what you're
looking for. For example, if  you want to search for hams by city, you
would type:
	city city-name	  and hit enter
	(for example: `city Kankakee').

Other search choices are "call" (after which you would type a ham's call
sign),	"name," and "zip" (which you would follow with a Zip code). Be
careful when  searching for hams in a large city; there doesn't seem to
be anyway to shut off the list once it starts except by using control-].

Exit: type quit and hit enter to disconnect.

@endnode

