The National Technical Information Service runs a system that not only
provides huge numbers of federal documents of all sorts - from environmental
factsheets to patent abstract - but serves as a gateway to dozens of other
federal information  systems.

@endnode

@node t-fdabbs.fda.gov
US Food and Drug Administration

telnet @{"fdabbs.fda.gov" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open fdabbs.fda.gov\r'"}

Log in: @{"bbs" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'bbs\r'"}

The U.S. Food and Drug Administration runs a database of
health-information.

You'll then be asked for your name and a password you want to use
in the future.
After that, type topics and hit enter.

@endnode

@node t-forsythetn.stanford.edu
Stanford University

telnet @{"forsythetn.stanford.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open forsythetn.stanford.edu\r'"}

Account: @{"socrates" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'socrates\r'"}

Stanford University maintains a database of documents related to
Martin Luthor King.

At the main menu, type select mlk and hit enter.

@endnode

@node t-ipac.caltech.edu
NED-NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database

telnet @{"ipac.caltech.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ipac.caltech.edu\r'"}

Log in: @{"ned" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'ned\r'"}

The NED-NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database lists data on more than
100,000 galaxies, quasars and other objects outside the Milky Way.

@endnode

@node t-cfa204.harvard.edu
Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory

telnet @{"cfa204.harvard.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open cfa204.harvard.edu\r'"}

Log in: @{"einline" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'einline\r'"}

You can learn more than you ever wanted to about quasars, novae and
related objects on a system run by the Smithsonian Astrophysical
Observatory in	Cambridge, Mass.

@endnode

@node t-spacemet.phast.umass.edu
University of Massachusetts (Physics Department)

telnet @{"spacemet.phast.umass.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open spacemet.phast.umass.edu\r'"}

Log on with your name and a password.

The physics department at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst
runs a bulletin-board system that provides extensive conferences and
document libraries  related to space.

@endnode

@node t-metro.jussieu.fr_10000
Subway Navigator

telnet @{"metro.jussieu.fr 10000" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open metro.jussieu.fr 10000\r'"}

No log-in is needed.

The Subway Navigator in Paris can help you learn how long it will take
to get from point A to point B on subway systems around the world.

When you connect, you'll be asked to choose a language in  which to
search (you can choose English or French) and then a city to search.
You'll be asked for the station you plan to leave from and the station
you want to get to.

@endnode

@node t-madlab.sprl.umich.edu_3000
University of Michigan's Department of Atmospheric, Oceanographic
and Space Sciences

telnet @{"madlab.sprl.umich.edu 3000" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open madlab.sprl.umich.edu 3000\r'"}

log-in: name is needed.

The University of Michigan's Department of Atmospheric, Oceanographic
and Space Sciences supplies weather forecasts for U.S. and foreign
cities, along with skiing and hurricane reports.

@endnode

@node t-bugs.mty.itesm.mx
Cimarron

telnet @{"bugs.mty.itesm.mx" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open bugs.mty.itesm.mx\r'"}
(8 p.m. to 10 a.m., Eastern time, only).

At the	"login:" prompt, type bbs and hit enter.

Run by the Instituto Technical in Monterey, Mexico, this system has
Spanish  conferences, but English commands, as you can see from this
menu of available  conferences:

List of Boards

Name		     Title

General 	     Board general
Dudas		     Dudas de Cimarron
Comentarios	     Comentarios al SYSOP
Musica		     Para los afinados........
Libros		     El sano arte de leer.....
Sistemas	     Sistemas Operativos en General.
Virus		     Su peor  enemigo......
Cultural	     Espacio Cultural de Cimarron
NeXT		     El Mundo de NeXT
Ciencias	     Solo apto para Nerds.
Inspiracion	     Para  los Romanticos e Inspirados.
Deportes	     Discusiones Deportivas

To be able to write messages and gain access to files, you have to
leave a note to SYSOP with your name, address, occupation and
phone number. To do this, at any  prompt, hit your M key and then
enter, which will bring up the mail system. Hitting H  brings up a list of
commands and how to use them.

@endnode

@node t-yfn.ysu.edu
Youngstown Free-Net

telnet @{"yfn.ysu.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open yfn.ysu.edu\r'"}

At the "login:" prompt, type  `visitor' and hit enter.

@endnode

@node t-tudrwa.tudelft.nl
DUBBS

telnet @{"tudrwa.tudelft.nl" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open tudrwa.tudelft.nl\r'"}

This is a bulletin-board system in Delft in the Netherlands. The
conferences and  files are mostly in Dutch, but the help files and the
system commands themselves  are in English.

@endnode

@node t-bbs.isca.uiowa.edu
ISCA BBS

telnet @{"bbs.isca.uiowa.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open bbs.isca.uiowa.edu\r'"}

At the "login:" prompt, type bbs and hit enter.

Run by the Iowa Student Computer Association, it has more than 100
conferences, including several in foreign languages. After you register,
hit `K' for a list of available  conferences and then `J' to join a
particular conference (you have to type in the name of the conference,
not the number next to it). Hitting H brings up information about
commands.

@endnode

@node t-well.sf.ca.us
Whole Earth 'Lectronic Link (WELL)

telnet @{"well.sf.ca.us" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open well.sf.ca.us\r'"}

Itself a major Net access point in the San Francisco area, the WELL
is also a unique online community that maintains dozens of conferences
on every imaginable  topic (seven devoted just to the Grateful Dead).
WELL users are intelligent and opinionated; discussions are often
fast and furious. The Electronic Frontier Foundation was basically
started in a series of online conversations on the WELL. Although it
has a serious San Francisco flavor, it has users from across the
country (enough to support both East Coast and Midwest conferences).
For its conferences, the WELL uses PicoSpan software, which presents
messages differently than rn or nn. When you enter a conference, you
can call up a list of  "topics." Enter a topic number, and all of the
messages start scrolling down the screen, sort of like the music on
an old-fashioned player-piano. There is some  online help, but new
users are sent a written manual. See Electronic Mail for information
on access charges (one advantage to connecting to the WELL through
telnet is that unless you live in the Bay Area, it is likely to be
much cheaper than other access methods).

@endnode

@remark Telnet 'in a mess additions'

