@node f-aaoepp.aao.gov.au
ftp @{"aaoepp.aao.gov.au" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open aaoepp.aao.gov.au\r'"}

The Anglo Australian observatory maintains a collection of some of
its images of the southern sky for anonymous ftp. Available in 
/images.dir - see the aao_piclist.txt and aao_pr.txt in that 
directory for details.
@endnode

@node f-ftp.uu.net
ftp @{"ftp.uu.net" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ftp.uu.net\r'"}

Has Amiga programs in the `systems/amiga' directory.

Supreme Court decisions are in the court-opinions directory. You'll
want to get the index file, which tells you which file numbers go with
which file names. The decisions come in Word Perfect and Atex format
only.

In the usenet directory, you'll find "frequently asked questions"
files,	copied from @{"ftp.uni-stuttgart.de" link f-ftp.uni-stuttgart.de}


Available 24 hours.

@endnode

@node f-wuarchive.wustl.edu
ftp @{"wuarchive.wustl.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open wuarchive.wustl.edu\r'"}

For Amiga files look in the `pub/aminet' directory.

Dozens of directories with software for all sorts of computers. Most
programs have to be "un-compressed" before you can use them.

The `graphics/gif' directory contains hundreds of GIF photographic and
drawing images, from cartoons to cars, space images to pop stars.
These are arranged in a long series of subdirectories.

The `/multimedia/images/wx' directory contains GIF weather images of
North America. Files are updated hourly and take this general form:
`CV100222'. The first two letters tell the type of file: CV means it
is a visible-light  photo taken by a weather satellite. CI images are
similar, but use infrared light. Both these are in black and white.
Files that begin with SA are color radar maps of the U.S. that show
severe weather patterns but also fronts and temperatures in major
cities. The numbers indicate the date and time (in GMT - five hours
ahead of EST) of the image: the first two numbers represent the month,
the next two the date, the  last two the hour. The file `WXKEY.GIF'
explains the various symbols in SA files.

Look for recipes `usenet/rec.food.cooking/recipes' directory.

Available 24 hours.

@endnode

@node f-rtfm.mit.edu
ftp @{"rtfm.mit.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open rtfm.mit.edu\r'"}

The `pub/usenet/rec.arts.books' directory has reading lists for various
authors as well as lists of recommended bookstores in different cities.
Unfortunately,	this site uses incredibly long file names - so long they
may scroll off the end of your	screen if you are using an MS-DOS or
certain other computers.  Even if you want  just one of the files, it
probably makes more sense to use mget than get.  This way,  you will
be asked on each file whether you want to get it; otherwise you may
wind up  frustrated because the system will keep telling you the file
you want doesn't exist	(since you may miss the end of its name due
to the scrolling problem).

The `pub/usenet/misc.consumers' directory has documents related to credit.

The `pub/usenet/rec.travel.air' directory will tell you how to deal with airline
reservation clerks, find the best prices on seats, etc.

The `pub/usenet/rec.pets.dogs' and `pub/usenet.rec.pets.cats' directories
have documents on the respective animals.

Look in the `pub/usenet/alt.sex' and `pub/usenet/alt.sex.wizards'  directories
for documents related to all facets of sex.

This site contains all available FAQs "frequently asked questions" files for
Usenet newsgroups in the `pub/usenet' directory. For easy access, get the
`index' file.

6 p.m. - 6  a.m.

@endnode

@node f-ftp.eff.org
Electronic Frontier Foundation

ftp @{"ftp.eff.org" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ftp.eff.org\r'"}

Use cd to get to the pub directory and then look in the EFF, SJG and CPSR
directories for documents on the EFF itself and various issues related
computers ethics and the law.

The `pub/Net_info' directory has a number of sub-directories
containing various Internet resources guides and information files,
including the latest online version of the "Big Dummy's Guide".

Available 24 hours.

@endnode

@node f-gatekeeper.dec.com
ftp @{"gatekeeper.dec.com" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open gatekeeper.dec.com\r'"}

Recipes are in the `pub/recipes' directory.

@endnode

@node f-neeedc.umesbs.maine.edu
ftp @{"neeedc.umesbs.maine.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open neeedc.umesbs.maine.edu\r'"}

The Federal Reserve Bank of Boston uses this site (yes, there are
three 'e's in "neeedc") to house all sorts of data on the New England
economy. Many files contain 20 years or more of information, usually
in forms that  are easily adaptable to spreadsheet or database files.
Look in the `frbb' directory.

@endnode

@node f-town.hall.org
ftp @{"town.hall.org" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open town.hall.org\r'"}

Look in the edgar directory for the beginnings of a system to distribute
annual reports and other data publicly held companies are required to
file  with the Securities and Exchange Commission.  The `other/fed'
directory holds  various statistical files from the Federal Reserve Board.

@endnode

@node f-ftp.stack.urc.tue.nl
ftp @{"ftp.stack.urc.tue.nl" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ftp.stack.urc.tue.nl\r'"}

You'll find text files about the Esperanto artificial language in  the
`pub/ esperanto' directory.  6 p.m. - 6 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-lumpi.informatik.uni-dortmund.de
ftp @{"lumpi.informatik.uni-dortmund.de" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open lumpi.informatik.uni-dortmund.de\r'"}

If you're interested in one possible future of	computation, and also
are interested in global optimization problems, evolutionary  biology
and genetics, you might want to take a look at this server. For an
overview  on the field, you should get the file `pub/EA/docs/hhgtec-*.ps.gz',
aka "The  Hitch-Hiker's Guide to Evolutionary Computation".
Available 24 hours.

@endnode

@node f-ftp.santafe.edu
ftp @{"ftp.santafe.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ftp.santafe.edu\r'"}

Look at SAFIER, the SANta Fe Institute's Evolutionary computation
Repository. It's the most comprehensive collection of the field,
and has more online than you ever wanted to know on EC. Get
`/pub/EC/CONTENTS' for the  complete contents of this location. "The
Hitch-Hiker's Guide to Evolutionary  Computation" is available as
`pub/EC/FAQ/hhgtec-*.ps.gz'.  An introduction to  SAFIER entitled
"The Navigator's Guide to SAFIER" is available for A4 and US letter
size paper as `pub/EC/handbook/safier.ps.gz' and
`pub/EC/handbook/safier-US.ps.gz', respectively.
Available 24 hours.

@endnode

@node f-iraun1.ira.uka.de
ftp @{"iraun1.ira.uka.de" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open iraun1.ira.uka.de\r'"}

Run by the computer-science department of the University of Karlsruhe
in Germany, this site offers lists of anonymous-FTP sites both
internationally (in the `anon.ftp.sites' directory) and in Germany
(in `anon.ftp.sites.de').

12 p.m. to 2 a.m.

@endnode

@node f-ftp.netcom.com
ftp @{"ftp.netcom.com" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ftp.netcom.com\r'"}

The `pub/profiles' directory has lists of ftp sites.

@endnode

@node f-ncsuvm.cc.ncsu.edu
ftp @{"ncsuvm.cc.ncsu.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ncsuvm.cc.ncsu.edu\r'"}

The `SENATE' directory contains bibliographic records of U.S. Senate
hearings and documents for the past several Congresses. Get the file
`README.DOS9111', which will explain the cryptic file names.

6 p.m. - 6 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-nptn.org
ftp @{"nptn.org" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open nptn.org\r'"}

This site has a large, growing collecting of text files. In the
`pub/e.texts/freedom.shrine' directory, you'll find copies of
important historical documents, from the Magna Carta to the
Declaration of Independence and the Emancipation Proclamation.

The General Accounting Office (GAO) is the investigative wing of
Congress. The `pub/e.texts/gao.reports' directory represents an
experiment by the agency to use ftp to distribute its reports.

This is also a Project Gutenberg ftp site

In the `pub/e.texts/gutenberg/etext91' and `etext92' directories,
you can get copies of Aesop's Fables, works by Lewis Carroll and other
works of literature, as well as the Book of Mormon.

In the `pub/e.texts/religion' directory, you'll find subdirectories
for chapters and books of both the Bible and the Koran.

Available 24 hours.

@endnode

@node f-leginfo.public.ca.gov
ftp @{"leginfo.public.ca.gov" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open leginfo.public.ca.gov\r'"}

This is a repository of legislative calendars, bills and other
information related to state government in California.

Available 24 hours.

@endnode

@node f-whitehouse.gov
ftp @{"whitehouse.gov" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open whitehouse.gov\r'"}

Look for copies of presidential position papers, transcripts of press
conferences and related information here.

Available 24 hours.
@endnode

@node f-ra.msstate.edu
ftp @{"ra.msstate.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ra.msstate.edu\r'"}

Mississippi State maintains an eclectic database of historical
documents, detailing everything from Attila's battle strategy to
songs of soldiers in  Vietnam, in the `docs/history' directory.

6 p.m. - 6 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-seq1.loc.gov
ftp @{"seq1.loc.gov" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open seq1.loc.gov\r'"}

The Library of Congress has acquired numerous documents from the
former Soviet government and has translated many of them into English.
In the `pub/soviet.archive/text.english' directory, you'll find
everything from telegrams from Lenin ordering the death of peasants
to Khrushchev's response to Kennedy during the Cuban missile crisis.
The `README' file in the `pub/soviet.archive' directory  provides an
index to the documents.

6p.m. - 6 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-nok.lcs.mit.edu
ftp @{"nok.lcs.mit.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open nok.lcs.mit.edu\r'"}

GIF pictures of Hong Kong pop stars, buildings and vistas are
available in the `pub/hongkong/HKPA' directory.

For Movie reviews look in the 'movie-reviews' directory.
6 p.m. - 6 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-nic.ddn.mil
ftp @{"nic.ddn.mil" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open nic.ddn.mil\r'"}

The `internet-drafts' directory contains information about the
Internet, while the `scc' directory holds network security bulletins.

6 p.m. - 6 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-world.std.com
ftp @{"world.std.com" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open world.std.com\r'"}

The `obi' directory has everything from online fables to accounts of
Hiroshima survivors.

6 p.m. - 6 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-cs.uwp.edu
ftp @{"cs.uwp.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open cs.uwp.edu\r'"}

The `pub/music' directory has everything from lyrics of contemporary
songs to recommended CDs of baroque music. It's a little different -
and easier to navigate - than other ftp sites. File and directory
names are on the left, while on the right, you'll find a brief
description of the file or directory.

7 p.m. - 7 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-potemkin.cs.pdx.edu
ftp @{"potemkin.cs.pdx.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open potemkin.cs.pdx.edu\r'"}

The Bob Dylan archive. Interviews, notes, year-by-year accounts of his
life and more, in the `pub/dylan' directory.
9 p.m. - 9 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-ftp.nevada.edu
ftp @{"ftp.nevada.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ftp.nevada.edu\r'"}

Guitar chords for contemporary songs are in the `pub/guitar' directory,
in subdirectories organized by group or artist.

Photolog is an online digest of photography news, in the `pub/photo'
directory.
@endnode

@node f-pines.hsu.edu
ftp @{"pines.hsu.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open pines.hsu.edu\r'"}

Home of IndianNet, this site contains a variety of directories and
files related to Indians and Eskimos, including federal census data,
research reports and a tribal profiles database. Look in the pub and
indian directories.
@endnode

@node f-elbereth.rutgers.edu
ftp @{"elbereth.rutgers.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open elbereth.rutgers.edu\r'"}

In the pub/sfl directory, you'll find plot summaries for various
science-fiction TV shows, including Star Trek (not only the original
and Next  Generation shows, but the cartoon version as well), Lost in
Space, Battlestar  Galactica, the Twilight Zone, the Prisoner and
Doctor Who. There are also lists of various things related to science
fiction and an online science-fiction fanzine.

6 p.m.	- 6 a.m.

@endnode

@node f-atari.archive.umich.edu
ftp @{"atari.archive.umich.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open atari.archive.umich.edu\r'"}

The shakespeare directory contains most of the Bard's works. A number
of other sites have his works as well, but generally as one huge
mega-file. This site breaks them down into various categories
(comedies, poetry,  histories, etc.) so that you can download
individual plays or sonnets.

@endnode

@node f-ames.arc.nasa.gov
ftp @{"ames.arc.nasa.gov" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ames.arc.nasa.gov\r'"}

Stores text files about space and the history of the NASA space
program in the `pub/SPACE' subdirectory. In the `pub/GIF' and
`pub/SPACE/GIF' directories, you'll find astronomy- and NASA-related
GIF files, including pictures of planets, satellites and other
celestial objects.

9 p.m. - 9 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-coe.montana.edu
ftp @{"coe.montana.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open coe.montana.edu\r'"}

The `pub/TV/Guides' directory has histories and other information
about dozens of TV shows. Only two anonymous-ftp log-ins are allowed
at a time, so you might have to try more than once to get in.

8 p.m. - 8 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-ftp.cs.widener.edu
ftp @{"ftp.cs.widener.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open ftp.cs.widener.edu\r'"}

The `pub/simpsons' directory has more files than anybody could
possibly need about Bart and family. The `pub/strek' directory has
files about the original and Next Generation shows as well as the
movies.
@endnode

@node f-mtv.com
ftp @{"mtv.com" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open mtv.com\r'"}

Run by MTV VJ Adam Curry, this site not only has music news but Curry's
daily Cybersleaze celebrity report.
@endnode

@node f-nic.stolaf.edu
ftp @{"nic.stolaf.edu" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open nic.stolaf.edu\r'"}

Before you take that next overseas trip, you might want to see whether
the US State Department has issued any kind of advisory for the
countries on your itinerary. The advisories, which cover everything
from hurricane damage to civil war, are in the
`pub/travel-advisories/advisories' directory, arranged by country.

7  p.m. - 7 a.m.
@endnode

@node f-ftp.uni-stuttgart.de
ftp @{"129.96.8.13" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open 129.96.8.13\r'"}

Aminet ftp mirror cd aminet

In directory `/pub/doc/faq' resides a mirror of @{"rtfm.mit.edu." link f-rtfm.mit.edu}
Available 24 hours.
@endnode

@node f-slopoke.mlb.semi.harris.com
ftp @{"slopoke.mlb.semi.harris.com" rxs "ADDRESS term SEND 'open slopoke.mlb.semi.harris.com\r'"}

Look in pub/magic for text, fonts, gifs, etc.
@endnode

@node about "About this guide"
This guide started as a port of @{"IPWIN" link aboutibm} an IBM based
hypertext compilation about the internet. When I saw the Big Dummies
Guide to the Internet in guide format part of my original intention
with the port became redundant, instead I concentrated on using
the amigaguide format and arexx to create a primitive intuition type
shell for driving some tasks on the Internet with your mouse. This
guide is designed to work with the excellent communications package
Term by Olaf "Olsen" Barthel.

When you are online to your internet host using Term you can have the
Internet_address.guide open and by clicking on the telnet, ftp, or 
finger button next to a destination you will automatically transmitt 
the appropriate telnet, ftp, or finger command down the line. This 
Saves you having to type in the appropriate address. If you click 
on the name of the destination you will get more information on the 
site (including particular logons and passwords).

If you click on the telnet addresses in the detailed information
node for each site, it will transmit "open <ip or domain address>"
down the line. This is for those of us who exit from a site, but 
remain in a telnet or ftp shell which expects an open command.

As you can see I have added transmission buttons to many passwords 
and login commands as well. This is still a bit messy since it wasn't
always clear in @{"IPWIN" link aboutibm} which was the precise wording of some of these
commands. Where in doubt I did not add this feature to the entry. 

The bulk of the adresses and site information where clipped from 
@{"IPWIN" link aboutibm}, others from the @{"BigDummiesGuide.guide" link bdg}.

The way I use Internet_address.guide is to open Term up on @{"Workbench" link wbench}, 
size it so that it sits at the top of the screen with some room 
underneath. I then open Internet_address.guide and size it so that 
it sits below the term window. This way you can browse through 
Internet_address.guide, whilst keeping an eye on your term window. 
Moving between the two windows is as easy as a mouse click.

This project involved a lot of cutting and pasting so there is the
possibility of errors that I haven't picked up on. Not to mention 
the fact that some of the information may be dated. If you find any 
errors could you please post them to me so that I can include them 
in updates.

I'm also looking for information on more sites to add to 
Internet_address.guide, particularly sites in countries and, for 
topics not well covered by the guide.


FUTURE ADDITIONS

* More addresses
* Change the default telnet/ftp etc from domain address to IP address
  (This will take a little while since I haven't worked out an elegant
  algorithm to do this.)
* any good sugestions from yourself
* add more hypertext @ touches

Thanks to Roger Nedel for BadLinks v1.17 which came in very handy and 
is highly recommended

@{"Problems" link probs}
@{"Customisation" link custom}


Gary Gallagher
Melbourne
April 1994


Internet Address

gg@werple.apana.org.au


Physical Address

Gary Gallagher
20 Curran st.,
North Melbourne 3051,
Australia

@endnode
